Think Tank: How to act in time of crisis
When O2’s mobile phone network crashed last July leaving thousands of users unable to receive text messages or phone calls, customers were quick to react, taking to Facebook and Twitter to express their anger and frustration. Social media provides an emotionally devastating alternative to the human connection Photo: Alamy	By Rachel Bridge
8:37PM BST 22 Jun 2013
Comments
Instead of responding to customers’ complaints in a formal corporate way, however, the team at O2 decided to use humour to defuse the situation by replying to complaints with cheeky and funny – and occasionally risqué – tweets. It also posted a picture on its Facebook page of a squirrel saying sorry. The novel approach worked. Customers loved the irreverent tone of voice O2 had adopted and by the time the problem had been resolved, O2 had gained 60,000 new followers on Twitter. Nicola Green, O2’s director of communications, said: “Nobody wants a crisis, but to come out of a crisis like that having net positive sentiment within our social media was just amazing. People went from being very upset and annoyed with us to joining in the conversation and becoming our brand ambassadors.”
Forget everything you thought you knew about crisis management because social media has changed all the rules. These days, when disaster strikes it is no longer enough to simply put out a press release and hope for the best. You have to go to where your customers are and show them you are in control of the situation.
Richard May, a director of Spotter, a social media monitoring agency, said: “Social media has expedited the spread of a crisis. The days when a company could try to control the message through the traditional channels has gone out of the window because now everybody has a voice. A lot of companies don’t have any idea what is being said about them on social media and it puts them at a huge disadvantage.”
