What’s more, while in the past customers may have been prepared to wait patiently for a company to get back on its feet, the ease with which they can find alternative products or services via the internet means that loyalty can no longer be relied on.
Dominic Cockram, managing director of Steelhenge, a crisis management consultancy, said: “Customers will quickly move somewhere else if they feel there is a crisis going on and they are not going to get what they want. There is also a feeling that if you are having a crisis then maybe you are not running your business very well.”
The problem is that getting it wrong can be terminal. According to insurance industry research, 80pc of SMEs affected by a major incident close down within 18 months, and 90pc of those that lose their data are forced to close down within two years.
Disasters affecting SMEs can range from IT systems crashing to fire, flood or theft damaging premises; from reputational crises such as food contamination to questionable conduct by directors or employees. The problem is that, despite many cautionary tales, many SMEs still do nothing about managing a crisis until they are actually in the thick of one. Research commissioned by the British Insurance Brokers' Association found that less than half of the 750 SMEs asked had any kind of continuity plan in place, while a survey by AXA, the insurance firm, found that only 39pc of SMEs have business interruption cover.
The good news is that there is much you can do in advance to mitigate the effects of an unexpected crisis.
First, draw up a contingency plan. Get your management team to discuss worst-case scenarios that could affect the business. Then prioritise what would need to be done in the event of a crisis – and who will be responsible for doing it.
Remember that you may need to find temporary accommodation, extra staff to man phone lines, new supplies, new equipment and emergency funds to foot the bill for all of the above.
From this, create an action plan document which includes practical details such as essential telephone numbers, a plan of the workplace with technical details and information about where to meet – a local hotel, for example – if the workplace is inaccessible.
If disaster does strike, your communication strategy will be key. Appoint an articulate spokesperson, be honest about what has happened and explain what you are doing to fix the problem. Give a consistent message – what you say on Facebook, on your website and on any media outlets (if it gets that far) have all got to match. Above all, act fast, otherwise misinformation and speculation will quickly fill the void. Finally don’t forget to tell your staff what is going on. When a crisis hits they are often the last to know, which can create resentment. Rachel Bridge is an author, public speaker and journalist specialising in entrepreneurship and SMEs
