Emma Crosby: 'My first TV job paid £17,000'
Emma Crosby, the Channel 5 newsreader, tries to put money by but life in London, she says, offers too many temptations. Emma Crosby, the Channel 5 newsreader, tries to put money by Photo: Clara Molden	By Nick McGrath
7:00AM BST 22 Jul 2013
Comments
How did your childhood experience affect your attitude to money?
I had a great upbringing and I never wanted for anything. My parents are very normal, middle class and are very careful with money, so we went on one summer holiday a year, three weeks over August, and we lived in a nice house, but we had to be careful. By no means was there money sloshing around. There was always a budget, which I probably have forgotten about, but that was definitely our background. I remember being given £1 for pocket money and thinking when I got to the age of about 13, "I cannot live on this." I sat down my father and said "I really need more pocket money" and he was like "OK, I'll give you an allowance", but it had to cover everything, including all my clothes, so that was my opportunity to manage my own money or save it.
Only children are often spoilt by their parents. Was that your experience?
A lot of people presume only children are spoilt, but no, I don't think I was spoilt. I can say that hand on heart.
What was your first job and can you remember how much you were paid?
I was a Saturday girl at Marks & Spencer and we used to pride ourselves that we got paid more than my friends at Tesco. I think it was probably about £4.80 an hour, which wasn't a lot but I had nothing to spend it on. It used to add up quite nicely.
What was your starting salary on your first broadcasting job?
I did a postgrad in journalism, so my first full-time job – rather than freelancing, which I did loads of – was working for a company called The Money Channel. It lasted for about 18 months and it was a typical dotcom boom and bust, but I loved it. I think my starting salary was about £17,000.
Related Articles
