02 Jul 2013
Amber Atherton: 'I undercut my school by selling uniforms'
02 Jul 2013
Sarah Parish: 'I was down to a fiver'
30 Jun 2013
Why life's more expensive for the super-rich
25 Jun 2013
You've since worked for all the major news broadcasters including BBC, CNBC, GMTV, Sky and now Channel 5. Do the rates differ wildly?
There's a market rate, so no. I have an agent, and they're very clued up about the market rate, so everyone's pretty competitive.
Did reporting for The Money Channel help you deal with your own finances more effectively?
What I have taken away from that was a better understanding of risk, especially around 2008 when it was all "Isn't life great?" and then it all went wrong. There's no such thing as a free lunch and I probably think that more. I'm not a massive spendaholic but I'm probably now more cautious or more aware of having to be a bit more careful and plan for the future financially, whereas in my twenties I wasn't as much. Covering markets, you realise that if you're not prudent and a little bit frugal then you can end up in trouble later.
Would you describe yourself as a spender or a saver?
Probably a spender, unfortunately. I do my best at the moment to save, but honestly I find it very difficult. I don't know where it goes.
Have you blown your wages on exotic holidays or an expensive handbag habit?
No, I just find city life to be expensive. The lifestyle of my friends who don't live in a big city is very different. The opportunity to spend money is everywhere. You walk out of your front door to get onto the Tube and you walk past the coffee shop on the way into work and buy a lunch and you can spend a lot of money just on buying a sandwich or something. Then there's always drinks and dinner after work. So just by going to work and living in London, you end up spending so much more than I think I would if I had a different lifestyle. I have two little tan Jack Russells and they're very expensive.
Do you dress them in silk waistcoats and feed them caviar?
Buying them wasn't expensive. It's maintaining them. Because I work relatively long hours, I have a dog walker and it's incredibly expensive. It's worse than nursery. It's £15 a dog for an hour-long walk, which is probably quite competitive in London. Sometimes I have to go off to do an interview or go in to work a full day, I've got other stuff going on, and that will be two dog walks in that day. Then it all starts to add up; it's probably about £150 per week.
Does money make you happy?
Money makes life easier. To live in a world where you didn't have to worry about your next job and how you're going to pay your mortgage, which is now 17 years long, if those concerns were taken away from me then it would make my life less stressful and easier, but I genuinely don't think money makes me happy.
So have you been at your happiest when you've been earning most money?
No. I've been made redundant twice and the fear of losing my job I found far worse than the actual process of it. In that period of time when I was out of work I was still freelancing, but didn't have a regular bound contract. I actually really enjoyed myself and I was able to do different stuff. It was fine in the end, but I think for me, speaking at my age, I really enjoy job security. I feel happier in life if I've got a nice contract in front of me, like a couple of years.
What are the biggest lessons you've learnt about money?
That it's very easy to spend and very good to save, but it takes forever to save and only minutes to spend.
As a freelancer do you put by your tax money religiously each month or scramble it together at the last minute?
I've got an accountant who's quite strict. That's always taken care of, so I just give myself a monthly allowance. So that's all quite organised actually.
Apart from property, what is your most extravagant purchase?
Probably buying my car. Is that a bit boring?
Not if it's a Lamborghini …
No. It's a BMW X3.
No impulsive buys you immediately regretted?
I once saw a Damien Hirst, a skull with the diamond teeth, about 10 years ago. I think it was £4,000 or £5,000 and I didn't buy it and I've been thinking about it since because I should've done. It would've come up in value massively, wouldn't it? One thing I wish I hadn't bought was this ridiculous MaxMara yellow skirt for about £500, which I only wore once and it's absolutely disgusting; a total and utter waste of money.
Have you been more prudent with property investment?
I have, but it's been nothing to do with me and my shrewd financial moves. I've just been lucky in London. I bought my flat in Fulham when I was 25, so I was lucky enough to get that quite young. It was a two-bedroom garden flat, really lovely, and I bought it in 2003 for £400,000, which was still a lot. It actually went below £400,000 at one point at the crash, but I sold it last summer for £650,000, so I was lucky. I've now moved farther west into a bigger property for about the same price, which I'm now spending most of my disposable income on doing up. I've also got a managed property in Cape Town, which is rented as a holiday let for two thirds of the year and used by friends and family for the rest of the year. It just about breaks even and property prices have remained stable since I bought it. But if I can keep it that long, it could be a great part of my pension.
Any other investments?
No, that's it. Those two, and I have a pension – I stopped paying into it just as the stock market started rising, and then I restarted as the market started to fall, so my timing is brilliant. I don't have a share portfolio because I just don't have the time or discipline and that's what you need in order to manage it properly.
Do you give to charity?
There's this fantastic charity called SOS in Cape Town and I'm an ambassador for it. I give a monthly contribution to it and I've spent a couple of days with them, seeing what they do. It's great to know hopefully that my money's going to help.
Are you a generous tipper?
I usually just take what's on the bill as the recommended amount. So that's it, I'm afraid. Not that generous.
Do you gamble?
I quite like going horse racing. I really enjoy the races. I haven't been very much this year, but I went through a phase of going a lot. I quite like buying the Racing Post and looking at the form, and the most I've ever won is £600 on an accumulator at Ascot.
What do you like least about dealing with money?
I've never particularly enjoyed looking at my bank statement. I've always had that dread when you look at the ATM and press the button for how much you have got in there, or when you read your statement, or checking online and going through all the motions. That process has never been good for me.
