Andy Murray claims he is in a 'better place mentally' ahead of Sunday's Wimbledon final
Andy Murray admitted after his epic semi-final victory that this Sunday's final against Novak Djokovic will be a battle but that he was in “a better place mentally” than last year to claim the title. Relief: Andy Murray salutes his semi-final victory over Jerzy Janowicz Photo: HEATHCLIFF O'MALLEY	By Theo Merz at Wimbledon
11:18PM BST 05 Jul 2013
Comments
Asked his thoughts on taking on Novak Djokovic in a rematch of this year’s Australian Open final which Murray lost, the British No 1 said: “Tough match. I mean, him and Del Potro played an incredible match today. “I saw some of the stuff – they were playing great rallies and moving very well. It will be tough. "I’ve only played him once on the grass before, at the Olympics last year, and I’ll take that thought in my head when I play him on Sunday.” At that meeting Murray defeated Djokovic 7-5, 7-5 to reach the gold medal match against Roger Federer. He and the Serbian were close on the junior tour, but Murray said he now has more of a “professional friendship” with the world No 1. Related Articles
