“I still message him sometimes. We spend a lot of time discussing various issues in tennis and doing what’s best for the sport but I don’t think it goes more than that right now. "I hope when we finish playing it would be different but it’s just hard, because playing in big matches there’s a lot on the line and you can’t be the best of friends when that’s happening.”
Of their game styles, Murray said he and Djokovic were similar in their strong returns. “It’s probably the strongest part of our games. We both play predominantly from the baseline, we both move well, but it’s a different type of movement. "I probably move with more power and he’s much more flexible than me.” Comparing his mind set to that of last year’s final, which he lost to Federer, he said: “I think I’ll probably be in a better place mentally. "I would hope so. Because I’ve been there before and I’ve won a grand slam I would hope I’d be a little bit calmer going into Sunday. “This year’s been a little bit different for me because there’s been a lot of expectation. I was almost expected to get to the final from early on in the tournament. Last year when I won my semi I was very, very emotional. "Today I was just delighted to come through and have another chance at playing a Wimbledon final.” Despite the gruelling nature of his semi-final, Murray had time for some jokes. Asked what he thought Fred Perry would say to him now, he joked: "He'd say, 'Why aren't you wearing my kit',"
And in a referance to Djokovic's visits to a Buddhist temple after games, he concluded his press conference by saying he watches TV comedy to relax, adding: "I don't go to temple". Andy Murray
